It's clear from the chart above that the large marjority of the homesless are white, however because of the differing scale it is difficult to assess how other ethic groups have changed. We can normalise the numbers to see how homelessness has changed across ethinicities.

We can iterate over column and normalize only numeric values.

Normalisation will produce values [0 - 1].

In [318]:
for i, col in engdata.iteritems():
    
    if not isinstance(col[0],str):
        minVal = col.min()
        maxVal = col.max()
        normCol = (col - minVal) / (maxVal - minVal)
        engdata[[i]] = normCol

To assess the relationship between roughsleepers and population, we need to make sure we have no outliers.

By plotting with Bokeh, we can add an interactive hover-over.

In [29]:
# Import figure from bokeh.plotting
from bokeh.plotting import figure, output_file, show, ColumnDataSource

from bokeh.models import HoverTool

# Import output_file and show from bokeh.io
from bokeh.io import output_file, show

source = ColumnDataSource(joined)

# Create the figure: p
p = figure(x_axis_label='Total Population',y_axis_label ='Rough Sleepers',title="Rough Sleepers and Total Population",
           plot_width=400, plot_height=400)

hover = HoverTool()

hover.tooltips = [
    ("Borough", "@{Local authority / Region}"),
    ("Population", "@{GLA Population Estimate 2017}"),
    ("Rough", "@value")]

p.tools.append(hover)


# Add a circle glyph to the figure p
p.circle(x='GLA Population Estimate 2017', y='value',source=source)

# Call the output_file() function and specify the name of the file
output_file('roughsleep&population.html')


# Display the plot
show(p)

From this plot, we can see that both City of London and Westminster are outliers. We can remove them from our regression analysis to gain more accurate insights.

However, rather than just removing these outliers, we can perform a more robust method for removing outliers.

In [112]:
columnValues = joined.as_matrix(["GLA Population Estimate 2017","value"])

meanValue = joined['value'].mean()
meanPop = joined['GLA Population Estimate 2017'].mean()


meanVector = np.asarray([meanValue, meanPop ]).reshape(1,2)

from scipy import spatial

mahalanobisDistances = spatial.distance.cdist(columnValues, meanVector, 'mahalanobis')[:,0]

# We create a new figure where we use a color mapping and use the computed mahalanobis distances 
# as the mapping value

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(11,8))
plt.xlabel('Population')
plt.title('Mahalanobis Distances - Roughsleepers and Population')
plt.ylabel('RoughSleepers')
plt.scatter(joined['GLA Population Estimate 2017'],joined['value'] , c = mahalanobisDistances, cmap = plt.cm.Reds, s = 80, linewidth= 0)

Simple Correlation/Regression Analysis to predict roughsleepers in London¶

In [86]:
filteredjoined =  joined[(joined['Local authority / Region'] != 'City of London')]
x = filteredjoined.iloc[:,5]
y = filteredjoined.iloc[:,3]
import scipy as scipy
from scipy import stats
In [87]:
scipy.stats.pearsonr(x,y)
Out[87]:
(0.133245893692287, 0.5163952331940059)
In [88]:
scipy.stats.spearmanr(x,y)
Out[88]:
SpearmanrResult(correlation=0.41690942120884944, pvalue=0.034103716392532755)

We can see that the Pearson's correlation shows a negligible relationship between Population and number of roughsleepers. However, the Spearman's rank correlation shows a much stronger, positive relationship. This is likely because Spearman's rank correlation is a nonparametric measure and is thus more resistant to outliers.

To test this, we can selectively remove Westminster, and rerun the correlations.

In [106]:

We see that, the pearson's correlation now shows a strong, positive relationship.

As we can see from the rsquared value and the graphical representation of the of the regressor, there is a weak relationship between population and roughsleepers. However, there is still some predictive power to assess the number of roughsleepers based upon population. The difficulty is the assumption that a person that ends up on the street is in a given London borough in which they are unable to get a home because of the population size. It is likely that rough sleepers will move around London to where they have the best support network, access to ammendities or for social reasons. Without a better contextual understanding of how and why homeless people are situated in a borough of London, it is difficult to assess the predictive power of this simple linear model.

To assess the validity of the model, statsmodels offers a more indepth breakdown of the model:

It is important to note the differences in values between the r-squared value calculated by the Scipy and Statsmodel models.The difference in the two values is due to the inclusion of the intercept term in the Scipy model. Statsmodels OLS function does not add the intercept by default. Therefore, the Scipy model is more relevent in this context.

Due to the small sample size, evaluating the model using cross fold validation may be ineffective, as the size of the training set and test set would be too small to accurately assess the predictive ability of the model.

However, as this was just one point in time (2017), we still have limited knowledge on how roughsleepers and homelessness in each borough of London has changed over time.

There seems to be a positve relationship between both healthcare spending and spending on social protection. It is likely, that there is no causation here. We do not want to build a predictive model which looks to predict the number of roughsleepers based upon government spending which suggests that increasing government spending in related areas would infact increase the number of roughsleepers. However, what this may suggest is that government spending is having little impact upon the rising number of roughsleeprs, and infact, the proposed government spending of Â£100m may not have the postive impact that is expected.

Finally, we can also hypothesise that the average real earnings of a person in the UK may have an impact on the number of homeless and roughsleepers.

Looking at the chart, we can clearly see that as real wages fall from 2006-2011, roughsleeper numbers start to increase in 2010. We can hypothesise that the impact of falling real wages may not have an immediate impact on the number of roughsleepers, but the impact that continued decline in real wages may have on spending, and therefore business revenue. Many people may face losing their jobs over this time, which can lead into a decent into homelessness and sleeping rough.

It is difficult to assess the correlation between real wages and roughsleeping, especially as roughsleeping continues to rise with the increase in real wages between 2013-2015. However, much of the damage may have been done during the dramatic fall in real wages from 2006-2011.
